Gutach: Even more safety for pedestrians
They are less than 100 meters apart: on Tuesday the new B 33 pedestrian light at the village parking lot was put into operation in Gutach - within sight of the older town hall light.
Two plants so close to each other: intention or tortoise stroke?
This question was answered clearly by Gutach's mayor yesterday.
"The City Hall ampel was installed at the time because it secures the school path," Eckert explained yesterday.
The Kluser Ampel is safe for cyclists as well as bus passengers and the Bergle residents.
The plant, which was officially put into operation yesterday, was important for the crossing area Sulzbachweg/Kirchstraße.
We have the museum, two churches, Kurpark, the bus stop, a doctor and a bank as well as the traffic flow from the residential area ›Grub‹.
"With the high traffic and pedestrian traffic, another traffic light had to be used for their safety," says Eckert.
Peter Arnold of the Landratsamt Offenburg confirms this.
"According to current measurements on the B 33, about 12,000 vehicles pass through the community of Gutach every day, of which about ten percent are heavy goods traffic," Arnold emphasizes.
Therefore, the construction of another traffic light is more than necessary: "Security is just going on here," says Arnold.
A total of four traffic shows were carried out, a roundabout was also considered, but because of the narrowness in the crossing area Sulzbachweg/Kirchstraße again rejected.
According to Arnold, everything was tested during the location selection of the traffic lights before: "By means of a transporter specially loaded with particularly long logs, we tested whether these vehicles can exit from the Sulzbachweg to the B 33 without bending the traffic lights".
The traffic light system itself, which costs around EUR 15 000, is the "most modern of what is currently available on the market," explained Arnold.
The system is equipped with coloured LEDs that glow so powerfully that the lights can be recognized by the drivers, for example, even in the low sun.
And it is also economical: the older lighting systems consume about 100 watts, the new ones just eight watts.
There are three lighting systems per direction of travel.
Arnold explained the technology of the new system: It is equipped with two radar sensors.
If the pedestrian pushes the traffic light button, the upper radar sensor tests the traffic position.
If the road is clear, comes immediately green for the pedestrian, if not, it takes about 15 seconds.
Another radar sensor checks whether the green phase for the pedestrian can be finished.
"If a group or disabled people cross the street, the green phase will be extended, so everyone will get safely across the road," Arnold explained.
Of course, the driver had to think as a partner and observe the road.
This was not the case yesterday: the traffic light for pedestrians showed green, an upper-class vehicle ran through - in bright red.
