A black box in the car?
American road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that can be found in the dashboard of every car.
The devices that record every kilometer driven and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning offices to revise the outdated system for financing US roads.
The normally rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and are in favour of the government using the small boxes to record the kilometers driven – and possibly where they were driven – and then using the information to calculate tax rulings.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of concerns about data protection.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
"It's nothing we're going to use," said Hasan Ikhrata, Managing Director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record the miles driven with all California drivers in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is financed by taxes, pays the Americans at the pump, is bankrupt.
But in America, not as much fuel as it used to be.
Cars consume less fuel.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 Eurocents per litre) has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by a cent at high fuel prices.
"The fuel tax is simply not sustainable," says Lee Munnich, an expert in traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state has recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a miles-based payment system.
"This is the most useful alternative in the long term," he said.
Bureaucrats call it a miles-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is popular with urban liberals, for example, the tax could be used to influence driving behaviour in such a way that congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
The Californian planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the federal state's ambitious, legally anchored goals on climate change.
However, Republican Bill Shuster from Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also pleased with the idea of letting drivers pay for their journey.
"This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole," explains Adrian Moore, Vice President for Guidelines at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in a report in 2011 called on Congress to move towards mile-based accounting.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move, responding to the concerns of rural MPs who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 riders for the country's largest experiment, is the most committed.
These drivers will soon pay the miles instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering such a thing.
Illinois tests it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where recently 50 volunteers were equipped with the equipment, drivers were skeptical of the government being able to follow any of its movements.
"Thinkings about Big Brother and such things were a big problem," explains Alauddin Khan, Head of Strategy and Result Management at the Nevada Department of Transport.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, Nevada's ACLU warned on its website: "It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult surveillance devices."
There was no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that the state can use to record the kilometers driven, but not exactly when and where.
According to Khan, this would also reassure the public.
Hunting for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not start to help states with the taxation of motorists.
Rather, their aim was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are to pay on the basis of the miles driven.
But the devices tested by her are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded," said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programmes have made major mistakes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they don't choose any equipment at all and instead pay a flat-rate fee based on the average miles driven by all the citizens of the state.
Others hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more functions than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxation device that can also pay parking fees, pay insurance only for miles driven, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, allowing drivers to avoid traffic jams.
"Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system," says a city planning document.
However, some traffic planners wonder whether the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said that Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by increasing the fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or annual tax could be imposed on drivers using hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little petrol, so that they also pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is sufficient," explains Randy Rentschler, Head of Legislation and Public Affairs at the Commission.
When we do this, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and many other things.
