U.S. border: "super tunnel" discovered for drug smuggling
At the border between Mexico and the United States, investigators discovered and shut down a "super tunnel" to smuggle drugs.
According to the U.S. customs authorities, the more than 500 metre long tube between Tijuana and San Diego was equipped with electricity, railway tracks and a ventilation system.
Three suspects were arrested, eight tons of marijuana and nearly 150 kilograms of cocaine were confiscated.
The tunnel had not been used, according to the data.
"These cartels are stupid if they think they can dig themselves out under the radar," said U.S. District Attorney General Southern California, Laura Duffy, at a press conference in front of a warehouse in San Diego, where one end of the tunnel had been discovered.
Addressing the drug gangs, Duffy assured: "If you continue to build such tunnels and try to use them, we are determined to make this a huge waste of your dirty money."
Both the US authorities and the Mexican security forces are in a permanent fight against the drug cartels.
Since 2006, more than 77,000 people have been killed in Mexico in connection with drug crime.
Designed by experts
Due to the complex equipment of the tunnel, the investigators assume that it was designed by architects and engineers and that the construction took about a year.
The track system was so equipped that electrically operated wagons could be used there.
On the Mexican side, the access is located in a building 80 meters from the border.
According to the authorities, a ladder leads 20 metres down to the actual tunnel entrance.
The tunnel has a cross section of 1.20 meters in height and 90 centimeters in width.
It would also have been appropriate to promote illegal immigration to the United States.
Two of the suspects were arrested in connection with the cocaine discovery.
The third, a Mexican, was arrested for the seized marijuana.
All three are threatened as a maximum sentence of life imprisonment, as officials said.
Since 2006, eight such tunnels have been discovered, according to the press conference in San Diego.
But it is the first time that cocaine has been found in such a tunnel.
Usually cocaine is smuggled in smaller quantities rather than through tunnels.
