Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to launch in the next few years.
30 suggestions were available, five are still in the race.
Far worlds.
Astronomers have already found more than 1000 planets in other stars.
No one knows if there are lives on at least some of them.
The choice is difficult: Should one look for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or looking for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering alien life?
These are the questions raised by those responsible for the European space agency Esa.
For their "Cosmic Vision" programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are intended to make research a decisive step forward.
The budget for such "L missions" is about one billion euros each.
The start is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were being discussed, five of them have now come to the narrower choice.
Numerous committees examine the proposals, follow up with the researchers.
In the next few days a final decision will be made by the Scientific Programme Committee.
A total of four major questions have been selected by Esa, to which the missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme, initiated in 2007, will find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and lives?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the proverbial dark.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this dark.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life be created there?
In order to address this question, the "Cheops" space telescope will be launched in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity will be investigated in greater detail.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
Using larger instruments, astronomers could map earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres and search for "biomarkers": gases that are considered to indicate biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, should ultimately provide information about the conditions for the emergence of life.
The magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation from it plays an important role with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be exemplified.
With the "Solar Orbiter" the Esa has already approved a mission of the M-Class (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is scheduled to start in 2017 and observe the surface and activity of the sun closely.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, Esa provides for the first of the three L missions of the Cosmic Vision programme.
The Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) probe is expected to begin in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is intended to investigate the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could guide physicists to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be combined.
How did the universe come into being and what is it made of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
Besides the common matter, which consists of stars, planets and living beings like us, there are dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and dark energy, through which the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know what physical laws were valid in the first fractions of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid" the Esa has already approved an M mission, which is scheduled for launch in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time throughout the sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race?
Of the 30 proposals, only two will be left at the end of the selection procedure.
According to many experts, "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for the detection of gravitational waves, has the best chances of being approved as an L mission.
This is what physicists mean by changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein had predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do this, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission includes a detector consisting of two or three probes, which is stationed in space.
In contrast to installations on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves created by the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four other proposals still compete for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is to explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which is to detect and investigate earth-like planets.
Among other things, proposals have already been made for the return of samples from Mars, for the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as for solar physics.
