Airlines started to charge fees for the first and second checked baggage items in 2008.
Passengers who tried to bypass these have therefore stuffed as much as possible into hand luggage, which means that the luggage compartments above the seat are often overcrowded.
Fees are a way to get passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee wasn't really about making money.
It was about the most loyal customers of Frontier, who had made it clear that it was becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who buy their tickets on the airline's website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger may be allowed to take a piece of luggage free of charge at Frontier's gate, but the next person will have to pay $100 for a similar piece of baggage.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's website and check-in procedures were changed so that passengers were informed of the fee before they came to the gate.
Frontier's new hand baggage charge only comes into effect in the summer, there is no exact date yet.
