He admitted the possession of cocaine in an earlier interview.
The lawyer was transferred after the police found out during their investigation against Scarborough that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta's house and put the drugs with a purity of 60 percent in a black golf glove under the lawyer's garbage can.
Shortly after delivering the drugs, Scarborough made regular calls to Ditta, who was at the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park for dinner.
The lawyer returned home, took the drugs, and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
It became known in court that Ditta was a "regular consumer" of cocaine after tests of Class A drugs had been discovered in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but refused to take cocaine and said that he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client and claimed that her discussion was subject to the 'lawyer's secret'.
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards, but they were secured and a hair sample was taken from him.
During the police interrogation, he stated that he ran an office at his private address as well as at the workplace and that clients would call him at home for legal matters.
In court, it was announced that he had called on major drug traffickers, some of whom he had previously represented, after significant arrests and informed them of what the investigators knew about them.
Attorney Anne Whyte said, "A criminal attorney should know better than everyone else that you don't break the law."
Ditta is accused of abuse of his position as a criminal defender, as he has become too involved with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not just that of a drug dealer, but that of a drug dealer who supplies his lawyer with drugs.
Part of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, for he was the lawyer of these people.
But this went far beyond the limits of a normal relationship between lawyer and client.
He counteracted the police investigations as much as possible so that they could continue to pursue their criminal activities.
Mr Ditta thereby discredited his profession.
He was too close to certain clients, especially Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta dismissed any misconduct and claimed, "If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to pass on information to Scarborough, I would not wait 15 hours, but do it immediately."
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead of Lancashire Police said, "Mr. Ditta has taken the step from a criminal defender to a criminal the moment he started buying drugs from organized criminals."
His addiction to cocaine led to hopeless compromise and made him receptive to the motives of leading members of organised crime who instructed him to obtain valuable information on police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and ensure trust and confidence in the public.
Ditta has betrayed this trust and tried to hide behind the façade of his profession.
The Serious and Organised Crime Unit of Lancashire led the investigation against Ditta, which also resulted in a conviction in three cases of possession of cocaine and judicial obstruction, which underscores our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We'll find you and bring you to justice.
