Security concerns in Mozambique are growing in the face of clashes between influential personalities
Thousands of people gathered in the centre of Maputo under the watchful eye of the statue of Samora Machel, the founder of the state and first president of Mozambique, to voice peace calls at a rare public demonstration.
"We want peace again, we want stability," said Vanessa de Sousa, managing director of an investment company.
For fear of the future of the country, she exchanged her business clothes for a T-shirt with the inscription "We demand security" in Portuguese and joined the crowd on Thursday in the capital's Independence Square.
For two weeks now, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, which have been among the worst battles since the peace agreement over 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a notorious rebel movement, initially supported by White-ruled Rhodesia and later by South Africa's apartheid government in an effort to destabilize the country's independent government.
After the 1992 peace treaty, she became an opposition party.
Analysts consider it unlikely that the country will fall back into a full-blown conflict, but recent events have alarmed foreign investors and locals.
A lot is at stake for the fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge gas deposits off the coast and coal deposits in the northwest could bring investments of over 50 billion US dollars from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the USA into the country over the next few years.
The ruling Frelimo party, the dominant force since 1975, and Renamo blame each other for the tensions.
Renamo claims that the government has provoked the recent clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofala, a traditional stronghold of Renamo, on 17 October.
The attacks on the former rebels escalated when government troops attacked Renamo bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the leader of the group, Renamo's spokesman told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for the clashes and accuses the organization of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza has tried to downplay concerns about instability.
On Wednesday, he told AFP, the French news agency, that Dhlakama sees himself as a "loser" who "will use all his remaining forces to prove that he can impose his decisions on the government."
Both Frelimo and Renamo stress that they want to avoid a war.
However, concerns have increased since Mazanga was quoted saying that Renamo abandoned the 1992 peace agreement.
He explained to the FT that he meant that Frelimo no longer respected the agreement.
"Our vision is to start negotiations again and seriously," said Mazanga.
Earlier talks between the parties have contributed little to the resolution of the tensions fueled by a series of clashes this year.
"We have two grown-up men (Guebuza and Dhlakama) who hit their heads," says Joseph Hanlon, lecturer at Open University and Mozambique expert.
None of them are good at negotiating and none are willing to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo, who is pushing for electoral reforms, has already declared that she will boycott the local elections in November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are planned for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted the use of violence as an attempt by an ailing movement to obtain concessions and financial concessions from the government.
Renamo's electoral successes have shrunk since 1992, while a newer party, the Movimento Democrático de Moçambique (MDM), founded by a former Renamo member, will probably improve in the elections.
Mazanga claims that Guebuza – whose resignation is due when his second term ends next year – wants to destroy the country's democracy.
"He does not want multi-party democracy, he does not want transparent elections, he does not want peace because he does not want to give up the presidency," says Mazanga.
It is unclear what capacity Renamo has, but she has made troublesome attacks on police stations and vehicles on an important north-south connection.
Most of the battles took place in the province of Sofala, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but where Beira is located, the port that mining companies such as Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio interrupted the use of the railway for a month after Renamo announced an attack on the line.
Mazanga replied reluctantly to the question whether Renamo would repeat this threat.
Renamo wanted "to warn the international community that things are not good in Mozambique," said Mazanga.
According to Fernando Lima, head of Mediacoop, an independent media company, instability has increased frustration with the government, as many people have already been worried about corruption, slow progress in development and a recent wave of kidnappings.
"People think that the government and the president are responsible for the country's future and that he should be the one to find solutions to the problems," he explains.
Omar Sultane, a demonstrator, said people just wanted stability.
"No one cares about Renamo and Frelimo, they just want peace and roads to be used again," he said.
