What happens to my e-mail on the way?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
Has the design of the Internet service e-mail been technically implemented in the same way as the conventional postal service?
In the design of the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have not taken care to create a stable foundation for a sound-proof correspondence.
Therefore, a conventional e-mail corresponds to an open postcard rather than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an e-mail to "Benni", are the two computers connected directly?
Anna's e-mail program or browser sends the mail to her service provider's mail server in the first step.
For example, if she has a GMail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run via several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call his provider.
Are conventional e-mails read along their way through the network?
Most e-mails are read by software robots several times on the way.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam mail, which is deleted immediately or at least sorted into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information that Google needs to place context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display appropriate links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also read the e-mails?
The likelihood of unauthorized persons reading an e-mail is extremely low.
In theory, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal opportunities to intercept or take note of e-mails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect e-mails from reading?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against read-through.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to mask the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even easy to recognize who has communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google on the e-mail market in Germany?
According to a August 2013 study by Convios Consulting, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the mainly privately used mailboxes.
While the shares of Yahoo-Mail had last fallen, GMail was able to increase significantly from Google.
