George Kerevan: European Unbundling gives Scots the choice
A new day, a new horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
This is the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire-backed border along the Hadrianswall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde template pointed out the potential economic benefits that would bring more freedom of travel in the rest of Europe, but this did not play a role in the headlines, as expected.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules if it is more favourable for them.
As Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continuing disregard for Brussels would only be a small concession in return for what one really wants from the Scots.
So, actually, no story.
And one that has come so far in the years that it already resembles a fossil: the first time I heard the "independence means passport controls" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should one expect an independent Scotland to dance according to the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project has officially died.
Across the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany – founded only this year – was able to win almost five million votes in the Bundestag election in September and effectively expel the Free Democrats (the equivalent to the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic resistance to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in conjunction with the straitjacket in which the national economy is forced to adhere to the single currency, many people believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The crisis of the euro has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave that.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe will find itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only option is to cut wages and public spending – inspired by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the Brussels "green" energy directives – a code for the subsidisation of French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity as it does with the United States and four times as much for gas.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All wage fixings in the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, there is a revolt, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and raise Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimation and has pushed up Europe's own economic policy, which has to fight against the weakened French economy.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU Front National has just won a decisive by-election, leading the ruling socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right-wing spectrum would automatically bring benefits to the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among the white French of the working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties perform well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the 'Europe of the (sovereign) nations' that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and Southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific region suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland with all this?
We can decide to be a region of (finally) small England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can do.
I suspect that Scotland could go quite well in a looser European network, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similarly-thinking countries is easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and in 2011 won a spectacular majority due to the rejection of the proposed (and implemented) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to get a austerity policy imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Getting to Grow Up Faster
Afro-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, as studies show.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe that epidemic obesity is a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned when her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the Pediatrics Association American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and were a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time calming parents – normally this is not a sign that puberty is coming quickly," explained Kaplowitz.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, as well as body odor, appear in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarchs (the occurrence of the first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the median age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 years in 1970.
"When breast development begins, it takes at least two to three years to reach the Menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early puberty in girls: The essential guide to dealing with this frequently occurring problem".
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually marks the beginning of puberty, but it is true that breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth boost before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
In case of rapid progression, tests by an endicronologist may be indicated so that serious problems such as tumours or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods to delay early menstruation and to prevent another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for medication or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs, but he admits: 'The suppression of puberty can alleviate behavioural problems and the feelings of girls, unlike their peers.'
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side," said Kaplowitz.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter was given her days at the age of ten.
Although there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, it was not emotionally prepared.
She came home scared and excited because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are caused.
Boys get into puberty similar to girls before.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a study in 2001 on girls between the ages of six and nine years, which establishes a link between body fat and entry into puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys have been growing facial and pubic hair before, the trend towards a full-blown previous puberty is not as pronounced as with girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
"We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to consult their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This can mean that you have to have a conversation sooner than expected," said Kaplowitz.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need the insurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than expected.
