Airbus says its rival adheres to a seating concept from the 1950s, when the average body size of the newly baptized jet set was narrower.
According to Airbus, investigations have been carried out to prove that an additional inch (2.54 cm) per seat increases the quality of sleep by 53 percent.
Boeing contests Airbus' figures on seating dimensions and says that it is not at the discretion of the manufacturers to decide how airlines balance fares and equipment.
The company also explains that the experience in the aircraft depends on more than the width of the seat.
"It really amounts to giving airlines flexibility so that they can do what they think they need to be successful," explains Boeing cabin expert Kent Craver.
They don't want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable.
You know your business better than anyone else.
For passengers, this is about more elbow freedom, but for manufacturers, it is increasingly becoming an issue that can affect sales.
Behind the dispute is a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least 700 billion US dollars after list prices in the coming decades, which could have a lasting impact on the export balance of the US or Europe.
As Reuters reported for the first time in July, the seat layout is the driving force behind the dispute over the new jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 percent more efficiency per seat in their latest two-engine long-haul designs than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 77-300ER.
Boeing's statements on the results partly depend on the comparison of the 777X with its ten seats per row with the original design of nine seats in the 777.
The increased cost per unit is still lower than for currently used machines with ten seats per row.
"Boeing therefore squeezes more seats into its aircraft to make it more competitive with our products," says Kevin Keniston, Head of Passenger Comfort at European Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say that full cabins with ten seats per row on existing 777s indicated that many passengers opted for the tighter arrangement, which could be accompanied by cheaper fares.
"Eighteen-inch seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is: from an economic point of view, the Airbus offering is controlled by the threat of the 777," says Mary Kirby, expert in cabin furnishings, founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The world-travelling jet sellers even carry band dimensions with them to measure the equipment in the competition.
Even if they offer comfort, all manufacturers also offer jets with a highly compressed design for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seater lines, but has not yet sold one according to its own statement.
Until recently, Airbus has stressed the importance of greater cabin adaptability and offered wide seats on the gears for some jets.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets, experts say that the call for a new industry standard is likely to blow, but could distract from the wave of 777X sales.
New anti-nicotine vaccine could spoil the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
Before human testing, further trials are needed, which may take a few years, but Professor Ronald Crystal from Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results were good.
"We are very hopeful that this kind of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried to stop using all the methods available on the market, but have had to experience that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches," says Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information on the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, so a smoker does not experience nicotine highs.
In experiments, vaccinated mice administered nicotine maintained their normal level of activity.
However, mice without vaccination would have taken a "time-out", the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brain.
The experiments are described in the scientific journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Vaccinations had to be given so often that they were expensive and impractical to maintain antibody levels.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower because it transforms liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it is certain, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette and thus prevent nicotine addiction.
But more likely, smokers would use it to stop.
"They then know that if they start smoking again, they won't enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that will help them to quit the habit," he explains.
British scientists said that the results were interesting, but at the same time warned that further research was needed.
