During most of the flight, passengers are already allowed to do so, but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian companies observe the decision to implement which US airlines have to do a lot of work, but they do not have immediate plans to change their regulations.
The CASA also stated that the announcement would be viewed, but stressed that the restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical flight phases in Australia still apply.
"CASA currently has no specific rules on the use of electronic equipment in aircraft", it was announced.
The subject is subject to provisions requiring airlines to maintain safety at all times and passengers to follow the safety instructions given by cabin crew.
Virgin has already had discussions with CASA about extending the use of his Wi-Fi entertainment system on flights and has stated that one is open to change, but these have to be initiated by the legislator.
"We would welcome a review of CASA's approval of electronic devices, because we are convinced that this would improve the customer experience after we now offer (wireless entertainment) during the flight," said one speaker.
Qantas said that they would remain with the current regulations until further notice.
"Our current directives stipulate that electronic devices may not be used during take-off and landing, and we do not have plans to change that at the moment," the company said.
The FAA rules apply to US airlines.
However, we are always interested in developments in regulations that passengers can benefit from, and will certainly take a close look at the FAA decision and the reasons behind it.
The impact of the decision on US companies varies according to the age of the fleet.
They must demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from mobile devices and change manuals, training materials, hand luggage programs and customer instruction.
"After an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any height," the FAA announced.
In rare cases with poor visibility, the crew will instruct the passengers to switch off the equipment during landing.
The group also recommended that heavier equipment be stowed safely under the seat or in the compartments above the seats at take-off and landing.
In front of the precinct derby against Schalke, fellow BVB supporters with flares had caused ugly scenes in the Veltins Arena.
Borussia Dortmund then announced severe consequences.
Before the Bundesliga's Friday match against VfB Stuttgart, the Ultras reacted with a silence - first.
It was an unusual, almost spooky acoustic that offered itself to the viewer in Signal Iduna Park just before the start of the Bundesliga match between the German runner-up Borussia Dortmund and VfB Stuttgart.
Most of the guests with their songs were heard.
On the other hand, the southern grandstand, where the most loyal of the loyal - and loudest - BVB fans stand, initially presented itself exceptionally quiet: no songs, no battle calls.
The podium of the Capo, which otherwise coordinates the joint cheering, remained unoccupied.
And at the very front of the grandstand, a large flag with the inscription "Sektion Stadionverbot" was blowing alone.
Only as goalkeeper Roman Weidenfeller entered the place as always as first BVB player, briefly cheered on.
When his teammates followed, there were loud vocals and waving scarves - but not everywhere.
In the central blocks 12 and 13 of the south grandstand nothing moved.
The fact that stadium spokesman Norbert Dickel once again listed the positive experiences of the last days - Derby victory, victory over Arsenal, contract extension by coach Jürgen Klopp - did not create a festive mood.
Only five minutes before the whistle, the capo climbed his podium - and the tension, which had been almost tangible with hands, was released in a loud scream when Dickel, as usual, questioned the mood on the ranks in the stadium.
As always, it was the turn of the south grandstand - and finally the loudest place in the stadium was here again as usual.
And at the latest, when the loud call "Derbysieger stands up" came with a whistle from the south grandstand, everything was again as usual.
The silence before was probably a reaction to the events of the past days.
Right in front of Bahnhofderby at FC Schalke 04 some of the BVB supporters had fired light rockets into the crowds and into the square - and nearly scored goalkeeper Roman Weidenfeller.
The game was delayed because of the chaotic scenes.
BVB boss Hans-Joachim Watzke had then received the tops of the Dortmund Ultras in his office - and if you believe Watzke's words, this was a rather uncomfortable appointment for the fan representatives.
"There will be massive cuts for the entire ultra-movement," the BVB boss announced on Thursday evening at a panel discussion in Frankfurt.
As an immediate measure, Watzke forbade the Ultras a choreography for the home match against the VfB Stuttgart.
"I banned that," he explained.
We cannot give up the zero tolerance policy on pyrotechnics.
In addition, the Ultras have been shown different possibilities of punishment - until Tuesday they now have time to choose one.
Otherwise, according to Watzke, the BVB will impose a sanction by the end of next week.
"That's going to be great," Watzke assured.
It is interesting to see what the reactions on the south grandstand will be like.
Pawnshops are booming in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings in a pawnshop in the Bendemeer shopping centre in Singapore to pay her daughters' school fees.
"My husband and I have just bought a house, there's all my money in it," says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars each month (about EUR 1,730) as an administrative employee and her husband also works, she explains that the monthly family income is not sufficient.
Indeed, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it has made its exchange, this week became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
The pledge of jewellery is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore require an annual percentage rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4% required by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping center.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that no verification of creditworthiness or proof of income is required, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region turn to pawnshops after families feel pressure from rising cost of living and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose fiscal policy in developed economies, families with lower and middle incomes are looking for pawnshops to compensate for the difference in the stuttering economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor's growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, described it as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
According to the Agency, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest budgetary debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week has just come out of a technical recession.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
"In the end, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the last two years have reinforced the trend towards pawning personal items, as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the 200 pawnshops of the city state are gold.
People say to themselves, "The price of gold looks good, let's pledge Grandma's gold chain and bring it back next month."
The largest Thai pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has experienced a 20 percent customer growth in its branches in recent months.
The growth in the deposit business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighbouring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is financing this with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it took this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders have fallen into the crossfire due to high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only have more favourable interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly increase debt.
"Customers lend goods that they already own, and the liquefaction of personal valuables does not increase household training," she explains.
The pawn lending business is increasingly accepted by society as short-term, secured financing.
Nor are all people who use pawn loans in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax's stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social class come to us.
"This includes wealthy people who lend something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses that have to bridge cash flow bottlenecks," says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
