Rescue package over 325 million Australian dollars for Tasmanian healthcare
The Australian government insists on the harsh conditions associated with the rescue package of over 325 million Australian dollars for Tasmanian health care to ensure that the government of the state cannot waste the money.
Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek has announced that the Commonwealth will take "immediate measures" to avert a crisis caused by an ageing population of the island state, a higher rate of chronic diseases and systemic restrictions.
Financing for a period of four years was decided upon after government consultations with independent Tasmanian MP Andrew Wilkie.
"The government has put together an emergency rescue package that we believe will address the unique challenges facing the state," said Plibersek today.
The $325 million package includes $31 million in emergency aid for electoral services.
A further 2600 surgeries, including orthopaedic surgery and grey star treatments, are intended to eliminate residues.
In addition, there is money for day clinics in Hobart and Launceston, better aftercare after inpatient stays, specialist training, services in the field of mental health and the introduction of a system for electronic recording of health data in local hospitals.
"These investments are in line with the ideas of the hospital staff concerned who told me that they are the best way to improve the Tasmanian health system," said Tanya Plibersek.
The minister insisted on a strict reporting and accountability of the Tasmanian government.
The state had to maintain the current level of funding in order to receive money from the Commonwealth and report monthly on where the additional funds were spent.
A three-member commission will be set up to ensure that the state provides health services as effectively and efficiently as possible.
As Wilkie explained today, the $325 million would only be of little use if "they were not accompanied by genuine reforms that would bring the public health system to a more sustainable course."
Nevertheless, he praised the government for having responded to his request for urgent assistance, which he had first expressed to the Prime Minister at the beginning of May.
"I am confident that federal aid will make a major contribution to removing the state's public health system from the care list," Wilkie said.
According to the government of the state, these election services will largely compensate for recent cuts.
But the health spokesman for the opposition at the federal level, Peter Dutton, believes that today's announcement is only a "pain solution".
"We are in today's situation because the Labor State Government has deducted 430 million dollars from the healthcare system," he told ABC TV.
It can't be that a state government rips almost half a billion dollars out of the system and puts 300 million into the Commonwealth and then pretends that it's good news.
Dutton asked Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar of the rescue package would be spent on additional bureaucracy.
