Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, according to a monitoring group
Syria has destroyed important chemical weapons and gas ammunition facilities, the global chemical weapons surveillance group said on Thursday, while in the north of the country there have been serious clashes near one of the sites where suspected toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed since the beginning of the civil war three years ago.
The announcement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) arrived one day before the date on
1 November, set up by The Hague-based Damascus organization to destroy or make 'inoperable' all chemical weapons manufacturing facilities, including all machines for mixing chemicals into toxic gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is basically the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all Syrian chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Damascus, however, still needs to start destroying the existing weapons and supplies.
It is believed that there are about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting took place in the city of Safira on Thursday, where experts say there was a chemical weapons production facility and storage facilities, as reported by the UK-based Syrian Human Rights Observatory.
The activist group, which is tracking the number of deaths through a network of activists in Syria, said on Thursday 120,296 people died.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the side of the government, 29,954 of them belonged to the army of President Bashar Assad, 18,678 being government-friendly fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 fighters of the opposition, many of them foreigners.
On 25 July, the UN estimated the number of deaths in this conflict to be 100,000 since March 2011.
This number has not been updated yet.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad's troops have been fighting the rebels in Safira for weeks, many of which have ties to al-Qaeda groups.
The Observatory said that there had been losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not give details.
The fighting underscores the danger posed by the chemical weapons inspectors, because their mission to free Syria from its poisonous arsenal is a race against time in the midst of a raging civil war.
According to OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team is "now convinced that it has seen and witnessed the destruction of all the important production and mixing/filling facilities mentioned by Syria."
Therefore, "no further inspection activities are currently planned."
Earlier this week, the inspectors had declared that they had completed the first round of inspections and visited 21 out of 23 sites designated by Damascus.
Due to safety concerns, the visit to two facilities was not possible, said the inspectors.
On Thursday, the OPWC stated that the two sites had been "dismissed ... and that the objects of the chemical weapons program there had been transferred to other mentioned facilities which had been inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
"I am wary of the bravery and courage you have all shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organization," said Ahmed Uzumcu, Director General of the Monitoring Organisation in a comment published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels in this civil war have been fighting against Assad's government and its security forces, many of which belong to the Alawites, to split Shia Islam.
Regarding further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said that there had been a strong explosion in an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday.
The cause of the explosion was unknown, he explained.
Anger over judgment for Bali bombers
Survivors and relatives of the 202 people who were killed in the Bali bombing in 2002 reacted angryly about the verdict for the last of the instigators who were brought to justice because Umar Patek was supposed to be shot in a civil manner.
Patek, who was on the run as one of the most wanted people in Southeast Asia for almost ten years, was sentenced to 20 years in prison yesterday for his role in building explosives for the bombing.
He could be released after 15 years if he was suspended.
The 45-year-old was found guilty of mass murder because of the attack on two nightclubs in the popular tourist district of Kuta, where 202 people died, including 88 Australians, and many others were injured.
A guilty verdict was also made in a series of terrorist charges, including a wave of explosive attacks on churches in Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
The prosecutor's office had demanded a life sentence, even if it could have applied for the death penalty for the man who, because of his reputation as a master bomb maker, is also referred to as 'Demolition Man'.
The decision has awakened painful memories at June Corteen, a mother from Perth who lost her 39-year-old twin daughter Jane and Jenny in the devastation caused by Patek and his co-conspirators almost ten years ago.
With tears, she said that Patek should have been sentenced to death.
I really think he should follow in the footsteps of the other guys.
"He should be put in front of a firing squad," Corteen told AAP.
I have to live every day with the fact that I won't have any more grandchildren and I will never see my daughters again.
The Sari Club was razed to the ground when, on October 12, 2002, shortly after 11 p.m., a massive bomb exploded in a small truck parked in front of the nightclub.
Peter Hughes was in Paddy's Bar, where only 20 seconds earlier a suicide bomber exploded a backpack filled with explosives.
He fell into a coma for a month after the attack and "died" three times while hanging on a life support system.
Hughes said that Patek deserved the same fate as the three other members of the terrorist cell Jemaah Islamiah – Amrozi, Mukhlas and Imam Samudra – who were responsible for the massacre and were executed four years ago.
Really, this guy should get the death penalty in front of everyone else.
To keep him alive – no, there is no reason to keep him alive.
Getting 20 years after he killed 202 people and injured many hundreds is not much.
Patek is the last of the Bali bombers to be tried.
He withdrew almost a decade from arrest, but was finally taken up in January 2011 in the Pakistani city of Abbottabad, where US forces killed former al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden just four months later.
During the trial, an FBI agent testified that intelligence reports indicated that Patek was in Pakistan to meet bin Laden with the aim of reestablishing the link between Southeast Asian terrorist groups and al-Qaeda.
"He didn't turn himself in," said Corteen.
Until recently, he has shown no remorse for how much suffering he has inflicted on other people.
The verdict was issued before the ten-year anniversary of the attack this year, which is being held with commemorations in Bali and Australia.
"There will be many tears this year," said Corteen.
Patek can still appeal against his judgment.
FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in airplanes (but do not have cell phone calls)
From departure to landing, passengers can now use their electronic devices for reading, working, playing, listening to music and watching movies, but not making phone calls, according to the new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
At a press conference, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained how quickly they would be implemented, depending on the respective airline.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals and the arrangements for storing the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic equipment in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in a statement.
Passengers currently need to switch off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not restart them until the plane has reached a height of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the approach, passengers must switch them off again and must not start them again before the plane has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the equipment also at take-off, landing and on the runway, the FAA explained.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Professional Association of Professional Flight Crews, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regime is implemented safely – and we work closely with the airline in this respect – both sides will benefit from it," said Glading.
To be honest, we are sorry to have to feel like watchdogs on this issue.
However, Internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data less than three kilometres remained prohibited, the Authority explained.
Passengers are asked to move smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to leave a jet of American Airlines in public because he refused to turn the device off while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops still need to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury in case they fly through the cabin.
Phone calls during the flight are also still prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not with the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board said national traffic safety expert on CBS News that mobile phones are still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause malfunctions in navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that air transmission can also interfere with transmission poles," says Rosenker.
A industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on FAA has increased to ease restrictions on use.
Critics like Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri believe that there are no valid security grounds for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies mention that up to one third of passengers forget or ignore the switch off of the device.
The FAA began to restrict the use of electronic devices by air travellers in 1966 after reports of disruptions of navigation and communication devices by FM radios carried by passengers had become known, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they do not care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years when the flight altitude is reached.
The pilots adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for increased use of electronic equipment under the new guidelines, said Huerta.
Today's electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when flipping.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Amazon.com is one of the advocates of easing the restrictions on the use of devices by passengers.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle E-Reader and made a test flight to identify problems, but could not detect any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said that he thought the interference with the equipment was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said that there were only isolated reports of pilots talking about a malfunction of aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to arrange the shutdown of the equipment by passengers in case of instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adaptation for travellers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
"We are pleased that FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not in conflict with security," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
