Is Europe's elite willing to do business with Britain?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing the economy together and defining what those who provide prosperity and work in the UK want to change in our relations with the EU.
To this end, we have commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of British business leaders and asked them what they think about Britain, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed over 1,000 business executives, representing about the UK's corporate sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We have found that the vast majority of companies are now exporting outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and growing, while the states in the EU are stagnating.
They hope that new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil will be favoured from the government side, rather than the long and tiring process of reforming the obscure EU institutions.
In their opinion, the majority of business leaders believe that control of these key competences should be brought back to Westminster on certain legally regulated issues – from antitrust law to product legislation.
There was general discontent about the internal market, as according to companies, the cost of the Brussels rules would now outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe’s trade zone – even 40 percent of large companies agreed with those who are traditionally the most European-friendly.
Finally, and probably most of all, our survey of business leaders revealed that a clear majority of the UK wants a course towards changing the agreement and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not on politics.
This insight, which is found among companies of all sizes and leading companies, shows that the economy is pushing for a "sensuous change" that the issue of action brings back to the UK.
There is a lot at stake – a change in the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a 16 percent change of opinion in favour of staying in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should have no doubt: this survey shows that the British economy is behind his plan for the renegotiation of the British conditions for EU membership.
It also shows that companies expect a significant shift in power relations back to Britain from a renegotiation.
A better deal for the British economy is possible and increasingly necessary after the eurozone is now moving towards a closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, as the results of our survey show, which means greater attention to trade for businesses and a fundamental change in the Brussels approach to regulation.
Alexei Miller of Gazprom describes pipeline in Bulgaria as the beginning of a new gas era
