Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA staff accused of sexual offences against Jonathan Lord
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) were charged with sexual offences related to children before charges were raised against child caregiver Jonathan Lord from Caringbah in 2011, as the Royal Commission for the Sexual Abuse of Children learned.
However, in the opening statement to the Commission, the YMCA stated that "the organisation had never had anything to do with an incident of sexual child abuse".
Managing Director Phillip Hare was questioned about a case in which a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences, and another in which a sports teacher at the YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted in 1991 of abuse of children entrusted to him.
Hare told Gail Furness, one of the Commission's assisting lawyers, that he had known about the first case but had not known the second.
He acknowledged that the opening statement of the YMCA to the Commission was also inaccurate in claiming that "there had been external reviews of the YMCA, in which the YMCA was recognised as at the forefront of child safety".
On the contrary, evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit conducted by the Department of Education and Communities in August of the year.
Hare, who started at the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that the management had failed "from me down" in hiring Lord and did not ensure that employees were aware of their obligations to report violations of the child safety guidelines.
Lord had been convicted early this year of sexual offences against twelve boys during his two years of work for the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare denied, however, that the YMCA had a cultural problem that had prevented employees from reporting Lord's child safety violations.
