Scientists were able to shed more light on the relationship between a dog’s tail and mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with their tail waved more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while it was the left side of nervous dogs.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive these subtle differences and react to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "People are well aware that the left and right hemispheres of the brain react differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noticed that in dogs, just like in humans, the right hemisphere is responsible for the movement of the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the emotions.
In order to learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail-wiring of their fellows, the researchers monitored the animals as these films of other dogs watched.
They measured the heart rate of the quadrupeds and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the tail moves in one direction, sometimes in the other direction
Professor Vallortigara said: "We have shown the dogs movies with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we have been able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right."
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog move the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the waving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail inclination was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog waving), her heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not communicate intentionally with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs have learned from experience what movements they should be worried about and when they should not.
He said: "If you have different encounters with other dogs and if you are more connected with friendly behavior with your tail in one direction and the right side produces a less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say that the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
John Bradshaw, an expert in dog behavior and guest scholarship at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the University of Bristol, stated that this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right is important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found out that dogs turn their head to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it's a happy dog.
Another research at the University of Victoria in Canada said: “Dogs tend to go towards a robot dog when his ‘tail’ is on the left and not on the right, instead of getting restless – just the other way around than in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could be caused by the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
"Although there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception," Bradshaw said.
But since their behavior is easy to record, it probably won't be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
