Pope Francis appoints first Cardinals in February
Pope Francis was to appoint new Cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time on 22 February, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest ranking clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope, and they are also the ones who elect a Pope, so that Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
Currently there are 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer take part in the papal election – this falls to a group of 120 "cardinals entitled to vote".
In a statement in which the news was announced, Father Federico Lombardi, a spokesman for the Vatican, said that there would be a meeting of all cardinals before the ceremony for the appointment of the new cardinals, also known as Consistory, was held.
"Pope Francis has decided to announce in advance his decision to convene the Consistory in February so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from all over the world can be planned," Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said that the number of cardinals entitled to vote will probably have fallen by February.
He explained that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as he needs to make the number of cardinals eligible to vote 120 more, and as many cardinals over 80 as he wants.
The consistory next year is important because it is the first since the election of Francis in March of this year, says Valero.
At present there is a certain overhang on the part of Europe, and in particular Italy.
"It will be interesting to see whether the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The Cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from all over the world who have the task of finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything on his own.
"Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him," Valero said.
He said that it was "well possible" for Francis to ask the Cardinals for advice.
But so far we have not been in this situation – this is all completely new.
