An Obama voter’s cry of despair
I have twice elected President Obama in the hope that change is possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by Republican blockade tactics
The blockade policy does not excuse the site problems of Obamacare, the drone attacks
Obama’s memoirs about the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what would have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm reading a terribly sad book right now.
It's a book I thought would cheer me up during the murky second year of my medical studies and give me hope again.
It is called "The Audacity to Win" and describes Barack Obama's memoirs of the 2008 presidential election.
When I finish my patient transcripts in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and breathed a speech.
The election became a landslide victory and newscasters stopped to show the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates cried with joy, and my parents gathered all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had 82% approval.
And then I close the book.
Switching to the present again is a bad awakening, as if you are being torn out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed possibilities.
In the years since I voted for the first time, something has actually changed.
But it's just nothing I could have imagined.
I acknowledge the great and versatile things Obama has achieved, from the adoption of the Affordable Care Act on Health Insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that party-political blockade tactics have overturned too many efforts to bring our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name but a few.
But after defending the Obama administration against colleagues and acquaintances countless times, I have come to the end of my attempts to explain.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The republican blockade policy cannot explain why foreign heads of state are allowed to interrogate, or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on American private life and why whistleblowers are punished to expose state misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why the public funding and spending limits are circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the results of a report which states that the White House's efforts to calm the media are the 'most aggressive... since the Nixon government'.
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
At 18, I should have understood that government work could contradict the previous political campaigns.
Obviously, the House of Representatives is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape the public debate.
But if I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confusing and unexplained alternative, he seemed unable to define his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fill the hope that we had heard of for so long.
But with Obama’s approval drop to less than 45% this week, the return to 2008 through this book has become all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
This week, I read a section in the book describing how Obama had to take a serious loss to Clinton in Pennsylvania's primary.
In a meeting with the election workers after the decision, he told his employees that they had to come back on course and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to rediscover our magic," he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree more with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris.
