Tourism: Descent to the Romans
A sewage canal from the Roman era is preserved below Cologne at a length of about 120 metres.
If you visit Cologne, you will not pass the cathedral.
About 157 meters the two towers rise into the sky and make it the second highest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who marvel at the two filigree church towers, suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne's underworld.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the Service Center of Cologne-Tourism directly at the Cathedral.
The tour begins unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies the city fathers wanted a car-right city, and therefore of the remnants of the old city walls only what was not too large stopped.
Therefore, most of the users of the car park today also rush past the Roman remains and only park their car.
But if you look more closely, you will discover an archaeological site in the Parkdeck D2 separated by metal bars.
About five meters high ruins of handplate-sized stones are visible.
"They are remnants of the Roman city wall, which was built in the second half of the first century after Christ," Schulze explains.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look into a dark, 15 meter deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which is unfortunately hardly noticed.
The next stop of the tour is the Praetorium, and here the participants descend again into the depths.
Here we experience the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Praetor of the CCAA.
A visitor would like to know what CCAA means.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means as much as "City Roman law and city of the Agrippinensers, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the emperor cult".
And the Praetorium is the former Palace of Governors, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the anteroom of the exhibition there is a tunnel access to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here at a length of about 120 meters.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers up the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After he gets the key at the cash desk, he leads the group to a 16-meter-deep, walk-in shaft.
"We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built its bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater, which was indispensable for the ritual washings.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read through changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe becomes part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is due to begin shortly.
However, a few years will pass before completion.
